segments.text: they were pre-vet and their mother was a public school teacher in baytown apparently something of a legend down there and anyway that was my first experience with that terribly smelly environment
And the other was to Houston just to see the big city with a couple of the Houston boys.
What else did you and your buddies do then on a weekend here that summer?
Walk the bullring.
Oh.
I did anyway.
And what were your alleged shortcomings that led you to be on the bullring?
Exercising freshman privileges.
Oh, okay, such as?
Well, to get away with whatever you could and not getting caught.
Well, mine began with not polishing brass well enough or shining shoes well enough and just the military things.
And I'd get a demurriate or two, and they built up a little bit along.

And this was because the first, well, June and into mid-July, I'd say, it took that long for me just to know whether I was going to drown or not down here in this place with trying to get on top of chemistry and just do everything.
And so...
I was doing, I was making an effort anyway.
I won't say I was doing my best, but I was making an effort to do the military things, but I came up short pretty often.
And I accumulated quite a few demerits.
And so I got to the point, I can't remember how many you were allowed before you had to start walking the bullring to get them off.
But anyway, that happened along in mid-July.
And as I got involved in that, then the pressures of the classroom began to subside a little bit.
I began to see, well, I believe I'm going to be able to do this after all.
Well, I began to join in.
some of the activities of my fish buddies, you know, of trying to do whatever I could get away with.
And then the demerits started accumulating a little faster.
Give some examples of the pranks that y'all... Well, the ones that, you know, that I think, well,
During my year, the first pranks that freshmen would do would be drowning out other students, either their fish buddies or upperclassmen.
Of course, that was after you'd gotten your technique down a little bit where you'd get the upperclassmen.
And so those were common things.
And then doing things with firecrackers
for upperclassmen.
I wasn't involved in this, but it is an example of one of the pranks that I remember from that summer.
We had one of the juniors, the second in command junior, was a guy with very poor vision.
And he had visual limitations, vision limitations, I guess.
And one of the freshmen turned a bottle of ink upside down

on a piece of cardboard right in front of his door and pull that out then of course and he came up and picked it up and of course got ink all over him and we had to scrub of course we had to take the ink off that all everybody did but we had firecrackers with
You could buy these, I don't know if it was Lindberger cheese, or it was a pretty aromatic cheese anyway, that you could buy in little sacks.
And this was a pretty popular prank at the time to open one of those and put one of the big firecrackers in it.
wrap it in plastic and put it in there and then light it and toss it down to the end of the hall where the CO or upperclassmen's rooms were.
And then they'd blast all over their door and everything.
And so you all did that in the summer?
Yeah.
As that summer goes on, how did you communicate with your family, your folks at home?
Letters, phone calls?
Just letters.
About how often?
Well, I think I started out maybe once or twice a week, probably.
I remember getting fussed at by my mother when I went home after summer school was over that I needed to write more often.

and how as you as summer school was over and you go home for three or four weeks how did you feel about summer school did you feel you'd made some progress well i felt at that point i felt pretty good about uh having passed everything and particularly the chemistry yeah uh that was it had been
represented a big challenge to me and so I certainly felt much better about that.
I felt that you know it was I was looking when I went home then I was looking forward to coming back in the fall and we had a lot of the guys that this had been a common item of discussion

in August toward the end of summer of the summer school program of how much more we were going to know than the other freshmen that came in in the fall and how you know we could get them involved and get them in trouble doing you know give them these things to do not as orders but you know just telling them why don't you go do this or that so we were looking forward to doing that sort of thing and
What did you do in that break at home between summer and fall?
Did you work on the farm?
No.
See, at the end of the last class, the last crop that we made was the crop between my junior and senior year.
Oh, okay.
in high school because my dad, while I was a senior in high school, my dad took possession of one of his restaurants that was in Winters.
He had provided the funding for a restaurant
to be built there by someone he knew from Brownwood.
And he felt he had to take it over.
He didn't like the management that was going on with it.
And this was just when Winters was beginning as an oil boom town.
And he was certain that it was going to be a good location.
So they moved down.
I stayed with an uncle, lived with an uncle to finish my high school year.
We were no longer associated with the farm.
The farm had been leased out for that year to my uncle.
So did you go back to the farm or back to town for that break?
I spent that interim in Winters.
So I don't remember anything.
Did you work in the restaurant?
I imagine I did a little bit.
I just don't have any recall of.
All right.
Then that fall, when you come back, how did you get here?
that fall, do you remember?
I may have hitchhiked.
And I'm assuming you had left your stuff in your footlocker.
Yeah, here.
And about how long did it take to hitchhike from Winters to

it was amazingly it was an amazingly efficient means of transportation I marveled at it at the time and I still of course now I guess you never think of doing that but I've made I have made faster trips probably my fastest trip
from here to Winters was by hitchhiking, because I got with an old boy one time, and golly, his car would go almost 100, and that's the way we went.
What route did you normally take?
From Angelo to Waco?
No.
Well, sometimes with hitchhiking, you get a ride to Waco, and then go across to Gatesville and Goldwaite,
and up to Brownwood, and then across to Winters.
Did you ever get stranded hitchhiking?
You know, left somewhere for two or three hours, or the whole night?
I don't believe I ever did.
And did you ever have a negative experience?
No, I really didn't.
I just assumed that there would be some of those.
I had some really positive experiences with...
Describe some of those.
I was picked up by... in Hearn.
I got a ride to Hearn, and then was picked up out of Hearn by a young man going to Temple, on his way to Temple, and he had a
an uncle and his family that lived, trying to think of the name of the little town.
It's about 12 miles this side of Temple, between Temple and Hearn.
Not Marlin?
No, it's a little tiny town.
We'll think of it later.
Anyway, this was a German farmer, and he had a young family, and so we stopped in there, and it was just about 1130 or around lunch.
I'm thinking that probably that was why the driver wanted to stop.
He was...

I didn't know it at the time but he obviously was also a German ethnic German individual and so at about lunch time if you had family nearby well you'd stop and take lunch with them and they were very open with me and had me in to eat lunch too and I that was a quite an experience to me to see this

german family and uh... very rather regimented uh... experience with all the children coming in very very well behaved a lot of you know just stair step down it seemed like there were five or six of them and uh... the father was very much in control overseeing the whole operation you know said grace in a very formal way and
It made an impression on me such that I remembered it through the years.
And in all of those hitchhiking efforts, you wore your uniform, you didn't use a sign.
No, I had a bag with an A&M symbol or sticker on it.
I kept that until we moved out here, and it had gotten so tattered.
I regret throwing it away then.
Now I regret it.
Was it normal to put your thumb up?
Mm-hmm.
Okay, you come back then in the fall, and to what outfit were you assigned?
Squadron 4.
I was in Squadron 3 in the summer.
And what was the nickname of Squadron 4?
Didn't it have a slogan or a nickname?
I don't remember it anymore.
This was a freshman squadron, see.
It was still a freshman, we were in a freshman, we had freshman squadrons at that time.
Oh, I see.
Why then?
Well, that's just, that was the custom.
See, they had had some, this was, this was the first or second year back from the annex.
Mm-hmm.
And so maybe I can't remember if this was the fall of 51.
I believe that's the first.
I think it was the first year back.
And that was the reason that they tried that summer school thing was because they were coming back on campus.
And maybe they had tried it out and had it.
I'm thinking that they had summer school for freshmen.

the last year they were out at uh and so where were we all quartered in the fall uh north north near sabisa uh-huh we were still over there in right in that group of dorms and at that time all of the see in the summer only two of the dorms two of the four you know

13 there's 14 15 16 and 17 are the numbered dorms they also have names which they go by now and I don't know those but in the summer we used two of those dorms we occupied two of those dorms in the fall all four dorms were occupied along with Walton Hall
in that month or so break between summer school and fall when your parents or anybody else asked you what A&M was like in the summer, what did you tell them?
It was hot and it was really hard.
I haven't really talked about the

the uh... not physical hazing but the you know the mental hazing that occurred that summer that was really intense such as well the problem it's just a matter of uh... is the mind games that go on with introducing yourself as a freshman and then they ask you asking you questions and
just harassment, you know, mental harassment, which was really, I don't think, hurt any of us and was really quite useful.
I mean, I think I grew out of the total thing, but I'll never forget the first day that the,

all the upperclassmen were back here and we went to this was the second morning that we fell out to go to breakfast and we marched in and when we came out of Sabisa to go back to dorm 14 which was just on the other side of the hospital at that time there was just a sea of civilian garbed

boys men whatever students out there and see they didn't have to wear a uniform but they expected you to know who was a junior and who was a sophomore and who was a senior and so if you would go to one and you whip out and there was a senior standing next to him and this was a sophomore well he would just let you have it for whipping out to him and not meeting that sophomore that senior first
So at about 11.30, I had made maybe, well, I'd gotten across the street and was maybe 10 or 15 feet down in the direction toward my dorm.
And they finally, they broke it up.
I don't remember who all was involved, but they wanted to get us back to our room

in time so we could fall out for for chow at lunch and it you know I was just I was just jelly practically because boy I had been you know yelled out and screamed at and it just went on all summer that way then.
Now uh in the fall the outfit you were in was not yet a veterinary a pre-vet no uh-uh was there any cohesion to it at all?
To the unit?
Was there any particular similarity of major?
No.
These were pretty large, numerically large outfits.
They divided the, there'd be more students in a freshman outfit, or there was that year.
And practically all of them were freshmen.
I mean, there was just a small number.
And you summer freshmen were unusual compared, because the majority were, that was their first day.
Uh-huh.
Was there a nickname for those of you who had been here in the summer?
No.
There, now there were some of them who, about, well I won't say

many a fair number of the freshmen in that class accelerated and adopted the class of 54 and others stayed with I'd say the majority stayed with class 55 but there's probably a third of them third of the students the guy that I came down here with for from Winters for example he he was a
aeronautical engineering.
Well, it was aeronautical engineering, I guess.
How did you register in the fall?
Do you remember?
I stood in line at SEBISA.
And who advised you on what to take?
Was there somebody who kind of reviewed it before you?
General, this was in, you went, we went, those of us that were here in the summer, the last week or two of summer school, well, we had to go to the Aggieland Inn.
Okay.
And they had a general studies division there.
And we had a...
There were counselors there, and then there were counselors, what was that?
There was a frame building where the chapel is now.
And we had to go there, too.
Some of us went over there for some things.
And you took a full load.
And at that point, as far as you knew, your plan was to go to vet school after two years?
Yes.
In the fall semester, that was very much what I planned to do.
All right, so what was the, describe the routine then for the fall with football season coming on and taking a full load.
What was the routine like for an aggie fish on a class day?
Well, the, you mentioned the board.
Now, my introduction to the board occurred

on college night what was that well this was the this was the first Monday night of class and we went to the Grove the whole student body went to the Grove and we had the the football team was introduced and the head coach talked to spoke a few minutes but in in in the proper order of
progression of things.
You know, a lot of the administration spoke.
Dr. Harrington, as I remember, he was the first one, or the main one, I guess he was president at that time.
And we had a board session after the introduction, after that was over, out in the
the grove of live oak trees.
It is between Wellborn Road and then dorm 17, I guess.
And who received the board?
Who got hit with the board?
Well, there were several of us that got a lick or two, just so that we'd understand how this.
And there were juniors.
juniors that did it.
What was the board made of?
It was a wood, but was it a baseball bat or a?
No, it, well, no, it was, it wasn't, it wasn't made out of, that particular one wasn't.
I've seen them that were, where they'd cut off the end a little bit and then plane it down very, very sharply.
But this was a one by three or something like that?
Is, yeah.
And did, did you have to drop your pants or?
No, just pull them tight, you know, you were,
You're supposed to lean over and grab as much of the slack as you could and stand up straight.
And that would diminish the possibility of heavy bruising.
And what did the other guys, what kind of noise did they make after each lick?
Did they yell or anything like that?
No.
Silent.
Yeah.
Wow.
And did anyone ever get hit high or low?
Someone would, you know, maybe it was something like that.
Were there any high or low shots where somebody got to return the lick?
No, not that evening.
And we had, that happened, I wasn't involved.
I mean, I wasn't present.
That happened during my sophomore year.
We had some hell-raising juniors in there.
in the outfit I was in.
Right, so in the fall routine, you're assigned to a room and the routine really gets going.
Who was your fish oil lady and what was described the room and the routine that the two of you had?
Well, we were crowded.
There were too many freshmen.
were the dormitory space, so I had two fish old ladies.
Bo Smith and Jack Lee were my fish old ladies, and we had a single cot that had been wired to the top above the,
double bunk beds, so we had three.
Three high.
How was it decided who slept in which of those?
Well, it was up to us to decide, and Bo Smith was, well, he volunteered for the top one.
He was, that's just a
trait of his personality.
He's very accommodating, always has been and still is.
He was a pre-vet, as it turned out.
We were not assigned together because of our major.
And Jack Lee was an accounting major.
And did y'all all become good friends?
Yes, and still, we still communicate.
And you had three desks, three study tables?
Mm-hmm.
So there wasn't much floor space.
No.
We had a footlocker under the table.
Was there a radio in the room?
Yeah.
And Jack Lee had a- Hot plate?
No, a turntable for a record player.
Oh, okay.
A little record player.
And he had a lot of the little records, were those 33's or- 45's.
45's, yeah.
And was it okay for a group of fish to play?
Just at certain times.
Oh, okay.

okay which meant that we played it uh as often as possible at other times uh all right and since it was an all freshman freshman dormitory then our freshman outfit you all didn't have to go clean up well we did but not we weren't permanently assigned there were in the fall we did have uh
You know, the CO never had to clean up his room.
Wiley Briscoe was the CO.
But this was something that the,
Well, it was one of the freshmen, I guess, that was assigned to develop the roster and maintain the roster of cleanup.
And as y'all went to Sabisa and then classes all day, academically, what was the routine for you that fall?
Taking a heavy load, more chemistry?
Yeah, and this was a
This is when I really had problems.
I started out in organic chemistry.
And I think everything would have probably been all right if it had been a level playing field.
But being one of the few freshmen in a course that was taken by

sophomores and juniors especially a lot of sophomores in there it was uh there were a lot of other things on your mind other than why were you who advised you to take that because you'd already had inorganic in the summer yeah and uh that i i don't remember that i guess uh how i wound up in it but i did and it
It was really unfortunate because I wound up dropping, basically dropping it, but it was a WL because I was just out of my element.
Who did you turn to for advice?
I can't remember the name of...
This was in the...
It was Austin Curley over at...

no i don't i remember him but i don't remember i didn't have a contact with him at that time did did everything else go okay that fall yeah but um well i also i had well i i can't remember if i made what
